1

00:00:00,280  -->  00:00:03,520
Here we'll work together through the solution for

2

00:00:03,520  -->  00:00:06,440
this simulating from the null hypothesis notebook.

3

00:00:06,440  -->  00:00:11,170
This first part, we're just reading in our data and importing some of our libraries,

4

00:00:11,170  -->  00:00:13,640
and then the very first question,

5

00:00:13,640  -->  00:00:17,440
we're supposed to set up the correct null and alternative hypothesis.

6

00:00:17,440  -->  00:00:20,240
Let's look at the wording associated with this question

7

00:00:20,240  -->  00:00:24,820
and see what indicates why the null and alternative would look like this.

8

00:00:24,820  -->  00:00:28,650
In general, it says, what if you're interested in studying whether the average height for

9

00:00:28,650  -->  00:00:32,760
coffee drinkers is the same as for non-coffee drinkers?

10

00:00:32,760  -->  00:00:34,950
In this case, there's no indication that you

11

00:00:34,950  -->  00:00:37,530
care about which direction the heights might go.

12

00:00:37,530  -->  00:00:39,650
You don't say anything about,

13

00:00:39,650  -->  00:00:41,810
we think that coffee drinkers will be

14

00:00:41,810  -->  00:00:44,430
taller or we think that coffee drinkers will be shorter.

15

00:00:44,430  -->  00:00:47,240
We just say, are they the same?

16

00:00:47,240  -->  00:00:51,980
Because of this, the test that we want to do is a not equal to test.

17

00:00:51,980  -->  00:00:55,660
This says that the average for the coffee drinkers

18

00:00:55,660  -->  00:00:59,920
versus the average for the non-coffee drinkers is not equal to zero,

19

00:00:59,920  -->  00:01:04,440
is our alternative, and our null is basically the opposite of that, so it's equal to.

20

00:01:04,440  -->  00:01:07,940
In general, the null always has this equal to portion and

21

00:01:07,940  -->  00:01:13,000
the alternative has either the not equal to or greater than or less than portion.

22

00:01:13,000  -->  00:01:16,060
In this case, because there's no indication of direction,

23

00:01:16,060  -->  00:01:19,480
we would just use a not equal to alternative.

24

00:01:19,480  -->  00:01:22,995
In the second case, it's worded a little bit different,

25

00:01:22,995  -->  00:01:26,590
so if you're interested in studying whether the average height

26

00:01:26,590  -->  00:01:30,490
for coffee drinkers is less than for non-coffee drinkers.

27

00:01:30,490  -->  00:01:33,710
Remember, the thing that you want to test or the indication of

28

00:01:33,710  -->  00:01:37,870
the direction you want to test should show up in the alternative hypothesis.

29

00:01:37,870  -->  00:01:41,190
This says that the average height for coffee drinkers

30

00:01:41,190  -->  00:01:45,610
minus the average height for non-coffee drinkers is less than zero.

31

00:01:45,610  -->  00:01:50,315
We believe that this number should be less than the non-coffee drinkers.

32

00:01:50,315  -->  00:01:54,255
That indicates that the less than should be pointed this direction,

33

00:01:54,255  -->  00:01:55,790
and basically then again,

34

00:01:55,790  -->  00:02:02,690
the null is the opposite side with the equal sign associated with it.

35

00:02:02,690  -->  00:02:06,570
Sometimes you'll just see equal to here and then less than,

36

00:02:06,570  -->  00:02:08,470
and that would also be okay.

37

00:02:08,470  -->  00:02:13,090
The main thing is that the alternative is set up in this direction.

38

00:02:13,090  -->  00:02:15,355
If you set up these subtracted

39

00:02:15,355  -->  00:02:18,250
the opposite direction and then you put a greater than on this side,

40

00:02:18,250  -->  00:02:19,570
that would also be okay.

41

00:02:19,570  -->  00:02:23,230
Those alternative hypotheses are equivalent.

42

00:02:23,270  -->  00:02:26,550
With that, the rest of this is like,

43

00:02:26,550  -->  00:02:32,290
how would we use data to test these sets of hypotheses?

44

00:02:32,290  -->  00:02:35,670
The first thing that we do here is basically very similar to

45

00:02:35,670  -->  00:02:39,100
a lot of the examples we've seen with the sampling method.

46

00:02:39,100  -->  00:02:44,250
You can imagine what we do is we have some large number of iterations.

47

00:02:44,250  -->  00:02:46,330
What we're doing is we're keeping track of

48

00:02:46,330  -->  00:02:48,830
the average height for the non-coffee drinkers,

49

00:02:48,830  -->  00:02:50,910
the average height for the coffee drinkers,

50

00:02:50,910  -->  00:02:54,030
and then basically the difference between these two heights.

51

00:02:54,030  -->  00:02:59,270
The first part here is just basically saying we're going to replace equals true,

52

00:02:59,270  -->  00:03:05,090
we're going to sample 200 times from the original data set that we have.

53

00:03:05,090  -->  00:03:08,610
If we actually look at this ahead of time,

54

00:03:10,130  -->  00:03:12,300
we have this dataset.

55

00:03:12,300  -->  00:03:14,850
Basically, what we're going to do is we're going to randomly choose

56

00:03:14,850  -->  00:03:17,990
200 rows from this dataset with replacement,

57

00:03:17,990  -->  00:03:23,265
and that's going to go into this Bootstrap sample placeholder,

58

00:03:23,265  -->  00:03:25,690
and then basically with that Bootstrap sample,

59

00:03:25,690  -->  00:03:30,285
we're going to look at the average height for those who drink coffee.

60

00:03:30,285  -->  00:03:32,700
We have this drink_coffee column.

61

00:03:32,700  -->  00:03:36,105
This is someone's height for someone who drinks coffee,

62

00:03:36,105  -->  00:03:39,800
and so you could say, if they drink coffee, what's their average height?

63

00:03:39,800  -->  00:03:43,080
If they don't drink coffee in this sample, what's their average height?

64

00:03:43,080  -->  00:03:45,660
Then basically we can append each of these things.

65

00:03:45,660  -->  00:03:49,140
We can append the average height of the coffee drinkers into this list,

66

00:03:49,140  -->  00:03:51,100
the non-coffee drinkers into this list,

67

00:03:51,100  -->  00:03:52,560
and then the difference between

68

00:03:52,560  -->  00:03:55,920
the coffee drinkers and the non-coffee drinkers into this final list.

69

00:03:55,920  -->  00:03:59,840
Basically, I would also recommend setting up this part to be

70

00:03:59,840  -->  00:04:04,260
consistent with however you set up your null and alternative hypothesis.

71

00:04:04,260  -->  00:04:07,040
In our case, we had coffee minus non-coffee,

72

00:04:07,040  -->  00:04:08,560
and so that suggests this way.

73

00:04:08,560  -->  00:04:09,960
If you set it up the other way,

74

00:04:09,960  -->  00:04:11,680
you'd probably want to just make sure that

75

00:04:11,680  -->  00:04:14,220
you calculate the differences in the opposite direction.

76

00:04:14,220  -->  00:04:15,585
There isn't a right or wrong,

77

00:04:15,585  -->  00:04:19,040
it just should be consistent with your null and alternative.

78

00:04:19,040  -->  00:04:20,820
This might take a little while to run.

79

00:04:20,820  -->  00:04:23,580
We are running 10,000 iterations.

80

00:04:23,580  -->  00:04:25,760
But once it completes,

81

00:04:25,760  -->  00:04:27,740
we're going to look at a bunch of statistics

82

00:04:27,740  -->  00:04:30,500
associated with each of these different groups.

83

00:04:30,500  -->  00:04:33,560
The standard deviation for the non-coffee drinkers is here.

84

00:04:33,560  -->  00:04:36,960
The standard deviation for the coffee drinkers is here.

85

00:04:36,960  -->  00:04:40,895
The standard deviation associated with the difference between the two is here.

86

00:04:40,895  -->  00:04:45,640
What we're doing here is actually looking at the sampling distributions

87

00:04:45,640  -->  00:04:50,240
associated with the average for the non-coffee drinkers versus the coffee drinkers.

88

00:04:50,240  -->  00:04:54,005
Again, this Alpha just makes it a little bit more see-through.

89

00:04:54,005  -->  00:04:56,765
If we wanted to, we could add labels to this.

90

00:04:56,765  -->  00:05:01,880
We could do label equals non-coffee,

91

00:05:01,880  -->  00:05:05,465
and then we could add another label down here to this one,

92

00:05:05,465  -->  00:05:08,995
and so we could do label equals coffee.

93

00:05:08,995  -->  00:05:15,525
Then we could add a legend to this.

94

00:05:15,525  -->  00:05:20,310
You can see the non-coffee drinkers' average heights are here.

95

00:05:20,310  -->  00:05:23,390
The coffee drinkers' average heights are here.

96

00:05:23,390  -->  00:05:25,745
Let's make sure that we got that set up.

97

00:05:25,745  -->  00:05:28,205
That all looks good. Basically,

98

00:05:28,205  -->  00:05:32,130
from here, whether it's stat sig or not is hard to tell,

99

00:05:32,130  -->  00:05:35,450
but you can definitely see there's some separation between these groups,

100

00:05:35,450  -->  00:05:40,290
and it definitely looks like the coffee drinkers are a little bit taller on average.

101

00:05:40,290  -->  00:05:43,005
Then this last part is just looking at the differences.

102

00:05:43,005  -->  00:05:45,710
You can see there's a little bit of

103

00:05:45,710  -->  00:05:48,740
a tail over zero which might suggest there isn't a difference.

104

00:05:48,740  -->  00:05:53,025
It just depends on how many samples are in this tail.

105

00:05:53,025  -->  00:05:55,900
Then overall, the distribution is fairly normal.

106

00:05:55,900  -->  00:05:58,720
The central limit theorem probably gave us that,

107

00:05:58,720  -->  00:06:02,150
especially with a sample size as large as 200.

108

00:06:02,520  -->  00:06:05,220
We have a pretty good idea of what

109

00:06:05,220  -->  00:06:08,460
this sampling distribution for the difference looks like.

110

00:06:08,460  -->  00:06:12,410
The next thing that we might want to do in this last part is basically say,

111

00:06:12,410  -->  00:06:14,610
well, what would this look like under the null?

112

00:06:14,610  -->  00:06:20,290
Well, under the null, we basically are saying there is no difference.

113

00:06:20,290  -->  00:06:23,730
Basically, it should be this distribution,

114

00:06:23,730  -->  00:06:28,030
but instead of centered here on some non-zero difference,

115

00:06:28,030  -->  00:06:29,445
it should be centered on zero.

116

00:06:29,445  -->  00:06:33,610
What we can do is we can say draw from a normal distribution,

117

00:06:33,610  -->  00:06:37,145
because that's what we know should be true under the null hypothesis,

118

00:06:37,145  -->  00:06:39,810
again, following the central limit theorem.

119

00:06:39,810  -->  00:06:44,190
Use the standard deviation of your sampling distribution for the differences,

120

00:06:44,190  -->  00:06:46,570
and we can do that 10,000 times too.

121

00:06:46,570  -->  00:06:48,010
We look at this distribution,

122

00:06:48,010  -->  00:06:52,085
you can see basically, here's what we think is true under the null hypothesis,

123

00:06:52,085  -->  00:06:58,210
and we might even plot this difference on top of it.

124

00:06:58,210  -->  00:07:01,960
We could do Alpha equals 0.05 here.

125

00:07:01,960  -->  00:07:05,015
0.5 here.

126

00:07:05,015  -->  00:07:12,430
Again, this could be null_true as my label.

127

00:07:14,150  -->  00:07:19,360
This one it's label

128

00:07:19,970  -->  00:07:25,940
equals actual_data or something like that.

129

00:07:25,940  -->  00:07:31,040
Then again, we could add a legend to look at this.

130

00:07:33,020  -->  00:07:36,590
The differences from my actual data are here,

131

00:07:36,590  -->  00:07:40,630
and the differences from my null hypothesis are this blue version.

132

00:07:40,630  -->  00:07:42,590
Then the question is basically,

133

00:07:42,590  -->  00:07:45,430
do we think this is statistically significant?

134

00:07:45,430  -->  00:07:51,110
One of the things that we could do is we could ask what proportion of

135

00:07:51,110  -->  00:07:58,310
our values under the truth fall below this zero or not.

136

00:07:58,450  -->  00:08:01,860
Let's just pull this second part.

137

00:08:03,050  -->  00:08:07,880
Again, here's the distribution of the truth and we could say,

138

00:08:07,880  -->  00:08:13,610
imagine we want vertical V line at zero.

139

00:08:13,610  -->  00:08:21,220
Something like that. We could change the color so that it stands out a little better.

140

00:08:21,680  -->  00:08:26,120
But the idea is this line represents where

141

00:08:26,120  -->  00:08:30,780
the null hypothesis thinks this should be. Put this part at the top.

142

00:08:30,780  -->  00:08:34,780
This red line thinks this is where the null hypothesis should be,

143

00:08:34,780  -->  00:08:37,400
and here's where our distribution is at.

144

00:08:37,400  -->  00:08:43,620
Then to get some value for how unlikely these things are,

145

00:08:43,620  -->  00:08:51,725
we could just ask what proportion of diffs, so diffs.

146

00:08:51,725  -->  00:08:53,600
Diffs are all of

147

00:08:53,600  -->  00:08:58,175
our simulated differences between the coffee drinkers and the non-coffee drinkers.

148

00:08:58,175  -->  00:09:01,175
We'd say of the diffs,

149

00:09:01,175  -->  00:09:05,840
how many of them are less than zero.

150

00:09:11,330  -->  00:09:16,240
I'm going to make this NumPy array in order to do this.

151

00:09:16,240  -->  00:09:18,260
It doesn't let you do it with list,

152

00:09:18,260  -->  00:09:20,900
so we'll change this to an array.

153

00:09:22,160  -->  00:09:25,450
Otherwise, everything else should stay the same.

154

00:09:25,450  -->  00:09:29,660
NumPy actually supports this pretty well.

155

00:09:29,660  -->  00:09:33,140
Here's all the ones that are basically down here in this tail,

156

00:09:33,140  -->  00:09:37,320
and we could look at how many of them there

157

00:09:37,320  -->  00:09:42,560
are and divide that by the length of all of our diffs.

158

00:09:42,560  -->  00:09:49,080
I would say only 0.3% of my values are down here in the tail.

159

00:09:49,080  -->  00:09:52,480
All the rest of them actually are above zero,

160

00:09:52,480  -->  00:09:57,130
suggesting maybe the coffee drinkers are taller.

161

00:09:57,130  -->  00:10:02,120
Hopefully this gives you a good idea of what we are looking for in the solution,

162

00:10:02,120  -->  00:10:07,820
and we will definitely be exploring these concepts more in the pages ahead.
